** composable-programs                                                        :skill:
   :PROPERTIES:
   :DESCRIPTION: Design philosophy for building chainable, composable automation programs
   :EMOJI: ⛓
   :END:

   PRINCIPLES

   Every program should do ONE thing well. A program that scrapes,
   filters, summarizes, AND notifies is four programs pretending to
   be one. Split them. Small programs are testable, reusable, and
   debuggable.

   Programs fall into five composable types:

   MONITORS — Watch a source for changes. Output: raw data + diff
   from last run. Examples: price-watch, rss-aggregator, sec-filings.
   Always store last-seen state so they can detect what is new.

   FILTERS — Take input data, apply rules, output what passes.
   Examples: keyword scoring, deduplication, threshold checks.
   Pure logic, no side effects, no external calls.

   TRANSFORMS — Reshape data. Summarize, format, extract fields,
   translate. May use LLM for summarization. Input structured,
   output structured.

   ACTORS — Do things in the world. Send email, post to Teams,
   capture to org file, create calendar entry. The only type
   allowed to have side effects. Always require human approval
   for destructive actions.

   META — Programs about programs. propose-programs, self-improve.
   They read the system state and suggest changes. They never
   execute changes directly — they propose.

   CHAINING RULES

   Use TRIGGERS property to declare what runs next:
     :TRIGGERS: filter-name, transform-name
   The output of the current program becomes available to the
   triggered program via __ctx.upstreamResult.

   Chains flow left to right: MONITOR → FILTER → TRANSFORM → ACTOR.
   Never chain an ACTOR back into a MONITOR. No cycles.

   STATE BETWEEN RUNS

   Programs that need to remember data between runs (last seen
   listings, previous prices, known items) should use
   __ctx.store.get(key) and __ctx.store.set(key, value).
   Store only what is needed for diffing — not full datasets.

   PROPOSING NEW PROGRAMS

   When proposing a new program, always specify:
   - Which composable type it is (MONITOR/FILTER/TRANSFORM/ACTOR/META)
   - What it chains FROM and TO (or standalone if none)
   - What PROPERTIES it needs
   - Whether it needs state storage between runs
   - Whether it uses LLM or is pure code (hardenable)

   Prefer hardenable pure-code programs. Use LLM only when
   human-like judgment is required (summarization, classification,
   drafting). A program that can be hardened SHOULD be hardened.

   CAPTURE TO PROGRAM

   Any captured item (URL, text, task) is a potential automation
   seed. When reviewing captures, consider: does this represent
   a recurring need? If the user captured a Craigslist search,
   propose a MONITOR. If they captured a report template, propose
   a TRANSFORM. If they captured a contact, propose an ACTOR
   that drafts periodic check-in messages.

   The inbox should empty itself by graduating items into programs.

